on't Ever Tell Anybody Anything‹ (in ELH, 44, 1977, S. 554–564). – G. Rosen, A Retrospective Look at »Catcher« (in American Quarterly, 29, 1977, S. 547–562). – W. Riggan, Picaros, Madmen, Naifs, and Clowns, Norman/Okla. 1981, S. 159–170. – E. H. Miller, In Memoriam: Allie Caulfield in »Catcher« (in Mosaic, 15, 1982, S. 129–140). – R. J. Huber, Adlerian Theory and Its Application to »Catcher« (in Psychological Perspectives on Literature, Hg. J. Natoli, Hamden/Conn. 1984, S. 43–52). – S. Shorin, The Language of S.'s »Catcher«, Tokio 1984. – S. Pinsker, »Catcher« and All (in Georgia Review, 40, 1986, S. 953–967). – A. Nadel, Rhetoric, Sanity, and the Cold War: The Significance of Holden Caulfield's Testimony (in Centennial Review, 32, 1988). – Critical Essays on S.'s »Catcher«, Hg. J. Salzberg, Boston 1990.

